SECRET STORE CSI DRIVER
Basically it is use to syncup the screts between the third party secrets with the Nativa Kubernetes Secrets(volume - mount it).

Install Custom Resource Definition for Secret Store CSI Driver using Helm. Pull the command to install it from the documentation.
Create AWS Secrets with secret name and key/value in it.
Install AWS Provider installer for CSI Driver
Create a policy in AWS IAM which has policy for secrets to allow or deny things. Mention ARN in the policy.
Create a IAM ServiceAccount in the cluster which will attach with the policy we created
Create definition file for csi driver (secretproviderclass). It has object details like secret name and secret type.
Create pod defintion file with Volume as CSI Driver info and mount the volume with container where it store all the secrets pulled from AWS Secrets.
Also mention the created serviceaccount details in the pod. 


1. Install CRD - Secret Store CSI Driver in the k8s Cluster.
2. Create secrets in the AWS (mysql-creds)
3. Install AWS Provider Installer for CSI Driver
4. Create a Policy in the AWS IAM - Just attach the policy to allow or deny details.
5. Create a IAM Serviceaccount in the cluster with the created policy attach.
6. Create secretproviderclass definition file with secret object name and type details.
7. Create a pod with volume, in the volume mention secretclassprovider details. Mount the volumes with the container. mention sa in the pod spec.
8. Using helm commnad enable the secretautorotation. Whenever the secrets key/value updated in the AWS secrets, sync will be done in the /tmp/

# kubectl get pod
# kubectl exec -it myapp-pod-asdc -- bash
# root@myapp-pod-asdc:/# cd /tmp
# root@myapp-pod-asdc:/# cat mysql-creds

Helm:
# helm show values secrets-store-csi-driver/secrets-store-csi-driver >> values.yaml
# helm list -n kube-system
# helm upgrade csi-secrets-store secrets-store-csi-driver/secrets-store-csi-driver --values values.yaml -n kube-system



